SIMPLE: fetter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fetter
<hw>Fet"ter</hw> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fetor</ets>, <ets>feter</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>feter⟦omac⟧s</ets>,
pl., OD. <ets>veter</ets>, OHG. <ets>fezzera</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fj⟦oum⟧turr</ets>, L. <ets>pedica</ets>, Gr. <grk>pe`dh</grk>, and
to E. <ets>foot</ets>. ⟦root⟧ 77. See <er>Foot</er>.]</ety>
<mark>[Chiefly used in the plural, <plw>fetters</plw>.]</mark>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A chain or shackle for the feet; a chain by which an
animal is confined by the foot, either made fast or disabled from free
and rapid motion; a bond; a shackle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] bound him with <qex>fetters</qex> of brass.</q>
<rj><qau>Judg. xvi. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything that confines or restrains; a
restraint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Passion's too fierce to be in <qex>fetters</qex> bound.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fetter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fetter
<hw>Fet"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<er>Fettered</er> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<er>Fettering</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put fetters upon; to
shackle or confine the feet of with a chain; to bind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My heels are <qex>fettered</qex>, but my fist is free.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To restrain from motion; to impose restraints on; to
confine; to enchain; <as>as, <ex>fettered</ex> by
obligations</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My conscience! thou art <qex>fettered</qex>⟦br⟧
More than my shanks and wrists.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fetterbush</ent>⟦br⟧
